'''Downdraft tables''' or '''downdraught benches''' are [[workbench]]s with built-in ventilation to capture dust, smoke, and fumes and draw them away from the material being worked on.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2LDqAgAAQBAJ&lpg=SA7-PA53&dq=%22downdraft%20table%22&pg=SA7-PA53#v=onepage&q=%22downdraft%20table%22&f=false |pages= 7–53 |title= Aviation Maintenance Technician Handbook - Airframe Volume 1 |year= 2012 |publisher= AMT Exams |author= FAA |accessdate= 2 April 2015}}</ref> They typically consist of a perforated surface whose underside is connected to a [[ventilation (architecture)|ventilation]] or [[dust collection]] system, to draw material through the holes and away from the work.

